BRAS=C3=8DLIA =E2=80=94 In an empty cafeteria outside Brazil=E2=80=99s Just=
ice Ministry, the
widow checked the time. She twisted her engagement ring. She sipped her
coffee. She checked the time again.

=E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m anxious,=E2=80=9D Rosane Gutjahr said.

She also felt the familiar rage that had guided almost all her actions
since Sept. 29, 2006. That was when an executive jet flown by two American
pilots, Jan Paladino and Joseph Lepore, clipped a Brazilian Boeing 737 over
a remote swath of the Amazon rainforest.

The larger plane =E2=80=94 Gol Flight 1907, from Manaus to Rio de Janeiro =
=E2=80=94
disintegrated midair. Every one of its 154 passengers and crew was killed.
The body of Gutjahr=E2=80=99s husband, Rolf, was found amid the wreckage on=
 the
forest floor.

The Embraer Legacy 600, meanwhile, managed to land at a nearby military
base. None of the seven passengers and crew on board =E2=80=94 all American=
s =E2=80=94
suffered injuries.

Today, Gutjahr hoped, she would find out whether justice would finally come
to the men she blames for her husband=E2=80=99s death.

The question of responsibility in what was then the deadliest aviation
disaster in Brazil=E2=80=99s history divided the Western Hemisphere=E2=80=
=99s two most
populous countries. In the American telling, the collision was caused by
Brazilian air traffic controllers. The pilots did nothing wrong =E2=80=94 w=
ere
heroes, even, for safely landing their jet under extraordinarily
challenging conditions. After being detained by Brazilian authorities for
weeks, Paladino and Lepore returned to a triumphant welcome in the United
States.

=E2=80=9CIt will indeed be a blessed holiday season,=E2=80=9D rejoiced Sen.=
 Charles E.
Schumer (D-N.Y.).

But in Brazil, the American pilots were found to be at fault. A criminal co=
urt
determined that Paladino and Lepore had flown while the plane=E2=80=99s tra=
nsponder
was inactive, effectively blinding traffic controllers to their jet=E2=80=
=99s
precise altitude. They were found guilty in 2011 of attacking the security
of an airplane and sentenced to 40 months of probation.

=E2=80=9CThe pilots=E2=80=99 failure caused the tragedy
<https://www.cut.org.br/noticias/tragedia-da-gol-falhas-dos-pilotos-norte-a=
mericanos-sao-reconhecidas-oficialment-56b7>,=E2=80=9D
future president Dilma Rousseff said as she campaigned for her first term.

Paladino and Lepore have denied all allegations of wrongdoing and have not
been charged with any crime in the United States. The U.S. National
Transportation Safety Board said the pilots were unaware of the
transponder=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cinadvertent inactivation=E2=80=9D and did no=
t violate any regulation.

Paladino, today a pilot for American Airlines, did not return requests for
comment. Lepore, who also continues to fly professionally, declined to
comment.

For George Santos, a life in Brazil at odds with his GOP politics
<https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2023/08/31/george-santos-brazil/?itid=
=3Dlk_interstitial_manual_16>

The impasse is now a case study in the difficulty of carrying out criminal
sentences on foreign nationals living abroad. After all appeals were
exhausted, Brazil requested the pilots=E2=80=99 extradition in March 2020. =
But this
year, the United States rejected the petition. It now appears unlikely the
pilots will ever return to Brazil to serve their sentences.

=E2=80=9CThe treaty between Brazil and the United States does not provide f=
or
extradition for this crime,=E2=80=9D their Brazilian attorney, Theo Dias, s=
aid in a
statement to The Washington Post.

Most of the victims=E2=80=99 families have long since given up waiting. But=
 not
Gutjahr.

She has dedicated her life to bringing the two pilots to some version of
Brazilian justice. She has sold her business to eliminate distractions. She
has joined the prosecutors=E2=80=99 case in an official capacity and spent =
hundreds
of thousands of dollars in legal fees to advance it. She has hounded
officials for status meetings.

Now, weeks after the United States denied Brazil=E2=80=99s extradition requ=
est,
Gutjahr, 66, was waiting on her last best chance at redress. The Brazilian
judge who convicted the pilots had ruled in 2019 that the pilots could
serve their sentence on American soil. She had a meeting this morning to
ask a senior justice official if that might still happen.

She finished her coffee. She felt that rage rising again.

=E2=80=9COne hundred fifty-four deaths,=E2=80=9D she said.

She stepped outside the building and lit a cigarette.

=E2=80=9CI will make sure the pilots pay,=E2=80=9D she said. =E2=80=9CI wil=
l fight until I go
crazy.=E2=80=9D

Then she blew out a plume of smoke, stamped out her cigarette and headed
into the justice ministry.
A midair collision over the jungle

The disaster began with a celebration. The American charter firm ExcelAire
had just bought an executive jet from the Brazilian manufacturer Embraer.
So on Sept. 29, 2006, executives from both companies toasted the purchase
and then prepared for the jet=E2=80=99s inaugural flight from the Brazilian=
 city of
S=C3=A3o Jos=C3=A9 dos Campos.

Lepore and Paladino were in the cockpit, Brazil=E2=80=99s Aeronautical Acci=
dents
Investigation and Prevention Center would report, to familiarize themselves
with the route and the aircraft itself. This was their first flight in
Brazil.

ExcelAire did not respond to a request for comment.

The jet was set to fly at 37,000 feet to Bras=C3=ADlia and then descend to
36,000 feet. Later, it would climb to 38,000 feet until reaching the
Amazonian city of Manaus. The flight plan would keep the jet within the
standard altitude as it transited the two-way air route called UZ6.

But as the jet took off, air traffic controllers authorized the pilots to
hold steady at 37,000 feet =E2=80=94 placing it at the same altitude as onc=
oming
air traffic.

That=E2=80=99s not unusual: Air traffic controllers routinely issue fresh
directives to pilots midflight. But two failures primed the flight for
disaster. First, the jet lost radio contact with air traffic control. Then
its transponder stopped transmitting its signal.

That meant air traffic control couldn=E2=80=99t see its precise altitude. M=
ore
crucially, it nullified the plane=E2=80=99s traffic collision avoidance sys=
tem,
which relies on the transponder signal to warn nearby pilots of its
location.

For 55 minutes, the plane flew hundreds of miles effectively in the dark,
without headlights.

Utopia to blight: Surviving in Henry Ford=E2=80=99s lost jungle town
<https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2023/07/28/fordlandia-brazil/?itid=3D=
lk_interstitial_manual_39>

Still, the ride was smooth, recalled passenger Daniel Bachmann, a dual
U.S.-Brazilian citizen who worked for Embraer. A journalist was quietly
working on a piece about the plane=E2=80=99s sale for Business Jet Traveler=
. The
American executives were asking questions about the Amazon below.

=E2=80=9CThen I felt this enormous bang,=E2=80=9D Bachman told The Washingt=
on Post. =E2=80=9CLike
we were sitting on bleachers and someone had pounded on it with a baseball
bat.=E2=80=9D
Alarms went off. The plane started descending. The pilots had no idea what
they=E2=80=99d struck: =E2=80=9CWhat the hell was that?=E2=80=9D Paladino e=
xclaimed, according to
the accident report.

The trees below, Bachman said, were getting closer and closer.

=E2=80=9CWe thought, =E2=80=98This is it.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D

But the pilots somehow made it to a jungle airstrip. It was a miracle.
Until it wasn=E2=80=99t: They soon learned they=E2=80=99d clipped a 737, an=
d all 154 people
on board were dead.

=E2=80=9CHorrible,=E2=80=9D Paladino would later tell the Today Show=E2=80=
=99s Matt Lauer. =E2=80=9CJust to
be involved in something like this. I would never have comprehended that it
would ever happen.=E2=80=9D

Anger was rising in Brazil. Lepore and Paladino were detained, released and
returned to the United States, promising to cooperate with the Brazilian
authorities.

Paladino denied allegations of wrongdoing.

=E2=80=9CThe facts of the case will come out,=E2=80=9D he told Lauer. =E2=
=80=9CWe just want the
truth to come out.=E2=80=9D

Then came the trial, the conviction and the sentence. Neither pilot ever
returned to Brazil.
