The case for extradition was never going to be easy. First, the United
States did not agree that the pilots had committed wrongdoing. Second, the
alleged offense did not appear on the 1961 extradition treaty signed
between the nations. Even if U.S. authorities had wanted to cooperate, they
would have had no legal basis to act.

=E2=80=9CExtradition is a big deal,=E2=80=9D said John Parry, an extraditio=
n scholar at the
Lewis & Clark Law School. =E2=80=9CAnd here, the alleged crime just doesn=
=E2=80=99t fit
within the treaty.=E2=80=9D

The Office of International Affairs at the U.S. Department of Justice,
which manages extradition requests, declined to comment.

Why beef-loving Brazil is so obsessed with an American steakhouse chain
<https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2023/06/20/brazil-outback-steakhouse-=
popular/?itid=3Dlk_interstitial_manual_57>

As it became clear the pilots would not return, Brazilians who lost loved
ones on the 737 believed they had little choice but to move on. Many
accepted some type of payout from the airlines amid a flurry of lawsuits,
but felt powerless to penalize the pilots.

=E2=80=9CIt was better to forget,=E2=80=9D said Jorge Andr=C3=A9 Cavalcante=
, former president of
the crash=E2=80=99s victims association, whose nephew died in the crash.

=E2=80=9CSpending your whole life fighting for justice, it was just too pai=
nful,=E2=80=9D
said Neusa Felipeto Machado, who lost her husband. Most families, including
Machado, ultimately accepted payouts from the airlines involved in the
collision. The association winnowed to just a few members.

Only one person, Machado said, never faltered.

=E2=80=9CRosane.=E2=80=9D

At her home in Curitiba, Gutjahr erected a small shrine to Rolf. She never
took off her engagement ring. She raised their daughter, 4 at the time of
the accident, to understand the case as she did.

=E2=80=9CThis wasn=E2=80=99t an accident; this was a crime,=E2=80=9D said L=
uiza Gutjahr, now 21.
=E2=80=9CMy father lost his life because of the recklessness of two crimina=
ls.=E2=80=9D

In interview after interview, year after year, Gutjahr seethed in comments
that seemed to evince as much thirst for revenge as for justice. In 2012
<https://www.camara.leg.br/noticias/374773-familiares-de-vitimas-do-voo-190=
7-pedem-punicao-de-pilotos-americanos/>:
=E2=80=9CThey say time diminishes pain; I tell you it does not.=E2=80=9D In=
 2013
<https://noticias.uol.com.br/cotidiano/ultimas-noticias/2013/12/12/e-um-abs=
urdo-diz-viuva-de-uma-das-vitimas-do-acidente-da-gol-sobre-reducao-de-penas=
.htm>:
=E2=80=9CThey have to get the maximum penalty.=E2=80=9D In 2021
<https://www.rdnews.com.br/cidades/conteudos/150235>: =E2=80=9CI want to ta=
ke their
home, I want to take their car, I want to take everything,=E2=80=9D she sai=
d. =E2=80=9CIt
won=E2=80=99t bring back my husband, but they are living normally.=E2=80=9D

In U.S., most UFO documentation is classified. Not so in other countries.
<https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2023/09/06/ufo-brazil-documents-class=
ified/?itid=3Dlk_interstitial_manual_68>

Attorney Daniel Roller, who for years represented Gutjahr in her quest,
said he has tried at several moments to counsel her that what she wanted
was not possible. The magnitude of penalty was unlikely to ever match the
magnitude of her loss. Perhaps, he once told her gently, it would be best
to let it go. Focus her life elsewhere.

She would hear none of it.

=E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ve never seen anyone so determined,=E2=80=9D he said.
A long and lonely quest

But as she sat in an expansive office at the Brazilian justice ministry,
her determination was put to the test. The news was not good.

Augusto Botelho, Brazil=E2=80=99s national secretary of justice, told her t=
he
government supported her. But that wouldn=E2=80=99t be enough to bring the =
pilots
to justice. That would be up to the United States, which was unlikely to
enforce a Brazilian sentence in its territory.

Botelho apologized that he couldn=E2=80=99t do more, wished Gutjahr the bes=
t and
led her out of the room.


She was alone again. These were the moments when she most wished Rolf were
still alive. There had been such joy to him. He would have known what to
say to make her feel better.

She stepped outside and lit another cigarette.

=E2=80=9CThere were 154 deaths,=E2=80=9D she said. =E2=80=9CSuch a complete=
 lack of respect by the
American justice system.=E2=80=9D

She perceived discrimination.

=E2=80=9CIs it because we=E2=80=99re from the Third World?=E2=80=9D she sai=
d. =E2=80=9CBecause we=E2=80=99re not so
strong like the Americans? But we have the same bodies, same pains, same
everything.=E2=80=9D

But the moment, when she allowed doubt and defeat to weaken her resolve,
quickly passed. She stubbed out the cigarette and was on to next steps. If
the federal judge presiding over the case issued a fresh injunction
ordering the sentence to be served in the United States, the government
would have fresh motive to pressure the Americans.

=E2=80=9CI will write the judge,=E2=80=9D she said. =E2=80=9CI will ask for=
 a meeting.=E2=80=9D

She wasn=E2=80=99t ready to give up her life=E2=80=99s purpose. Not yet.

=E2=80=9COne hundred fifty-four deaths,=E2=80=9D she repeated. =E2=80=9CI w=
